Without confounding, the regression slope of Y on X — the "seeing" estimate — should match the do-operator ATE. Both should recover the true causal effect.

::: {#80a4632e .cell execution_count=11}
``` {.python .cell-code}
seeing_slope = polyfit(X_rand, Y_rand, 1)[1]

ate_rand = model_rand.ate("Y", "X", values=(0.0, 1.0))
print(f"Seeing  (OLS slope):   {seeing_slope:.3f}")
print(f"Doing   (do-operator): {ate_rand.mean('Y'):.3f}")
print(f"True effect:           {TRUE_EFFECT}")
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
Seeing  (OLS slope):   0.402
Doing   (do-operator): 0.402
True effect:           0.4
```
:::
:::


::: {#cell-fig-seeing-vs-doing-unconfounded .cell execution_count=12}
``` {.python .cell-code code-fold="true"}
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(FIG_WIDTH, FIG_HEIGHT * 0.65))

rand_val = ate_rand.mean("Y")
rand_hdi = ate_rand.hdi("Y", prob=0.94)

ax.errorbar(
    seeing_slope,
    1,
    fmt="s",
    color="C1",
    markersize=8,
    label="Seeing (OLS slope)",
)
ax.errorbar(
    rand_val,
    0,
    xerr=[[rand_val - rand_hdi[0]], [rand_hdi[1] - rand_val]],
    fmt="o",
    color="C0",
    capsize=5,
    label="Doing (do-operator ATE)",
)
ax.axvline(
    TRUE_EFFECT,
    color="black",
    linestyle="--",
    label=f"True causal effect ({TRUE_EFFECT})",
)
ax.set_yticks([0, 1])
ax.set_yticklabels(["do(X=1) − do(X=0)", "OLS slope"])
ax.set_xlabel("Effect of X on Y")
ax.legend(loc="best", fontsize=9)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
```

